{
  "doc_id": "35331",
  "text": "Unlike mating preferences, cryptic isolation itself is not consistently strongest in parapatry, perhaps because behavioural processes that occur earlier in the life history are more effective at minimizing the costs associated with hybridization (Coyne & Orr 2004) . Another explanation involves gene flow, which is known to occur between parapatric populations [CITATION_1] . Homogenizing gene flow may have constrained divergence in cryptic reproductive barriers between parapatric populations of T. cristinae, as has been observed for other traits, such as colour pattern, body size, body shape, host preference and mate preference [CITATION_2] Nosil et al. 2003, in press; [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
